2. Literature Review

2.1 Temporal Networks and Influence Propagation

The study of temporal networks was systematized by Holme and Saramäki (2012), who introduced continuous‑time temporal graphs as a framework for modeling systems where edge activity is time‑stamped rather than static. For self‑exciting event processes — where past events increase the probability of future events — the foundational model is the Hawkes process (Hawkes, 1971), whose intensity function takes the form of a convolution with a memory kernel. Temporal PageRank (Rozenshtein and Gionis, 2016) extends the classical random‑walk interpretation of PageRank to time‑stamped graphs by exponentially discounting older edges.

Volterra integral equations provide the natural continuous‑time formalism for systems with memory. Their application to epidemic spreading — where the current infection rate depends on the full history of past infections convolved with an infectivity kernel — is developed in Diekmann and Heesterbeek (2000). The comprehensive operator‑theoretic treatment of Volterra equations in function spaces, including existence, uniqueness, and continuation theorems, is given in Gripenberg, Londen, and Staffans (1990), which serves as our primary reference for well‑posedness analysis.

To our knowledge, no existing work combines Volterra dynamics with semantic content‑dependent kernels, geometric regularization, and transaction‑value weighted Sybil resistance for knowledge propagation.

2.2 Semantic Similarity and Originality

The embedding of textual content into dense vector spaces via language models enables geometric treatment of semantic similarity. Originality can be formalized as distance from prior work in an embedding space; Shani et al. (2021) develop this approach for quantifying novelty in scientific papers.

Knowledge recombination networks. Recent work by Wang et al. (2025) introduces a hybrid graph and LLM approach that captures novelty through the combinations of knowledge elements that a paper brings together . Their method constructs a Reference Knowledge Co‑occurrence Network (RKCN) from cited works, extracts knowledge entities using LLM prompting, and propagates knowledge representations through Graph Attention Networks (GATs). The approach operates in four stages:

1. Knowledge extraction: Using prompt-driven LLM extraction to identify key knowledge entities from paper abstracts
2. RKCN construction: Building a network where nodes are knowledge entities and edges represent co‑occurrence within the same reference
3. Knowledge propagation: Initializing entity embeddings with SciDeBERTa(CS) representations and propagating through GAT layers
4. Novelty aggregation: Computing pairwise similarities between propagated embeddings to quantify knowledge combination novelty

This approach significantly outperforms content‑only and reference‑only baselines in novelty prediction . We adopt it as a core enhancement to our originality metric.

Spherical kernel density estimation. For compositional data with zeros—common in embedding spaces—Yoon, Choi, and Ahn (2025) propose a novel KDE method that exploits the geometric correspondence between simplices and hyperspheres. Using von Mises‑Fisher kernels, their estimator is consistent and asymptotically unbiased across the entire sphere. This naturally accommodates the normalized embeddings in our framework and eliminates boundary bias issues associated with Gaussian KDE. The von Mises‑Fisher kernel takes the form :

K_{\text{vMF}}(x; \mu, \kappa) = C_d(\kappa) e^{\kappa \langle x, \mu \rangle}

where $C_d(\kappa) = \frac{\kappa^{d/2-1}}{(2\pi)^{d/2} I_{d/2-1}(\kappa)}$ ensures proper normalization, with $I_\nu$ the modified Bessel function of the first kind. Bandwidth selection can be performed via plug-in methods  or rule-of-thumb selectors .

Spherical knowledge graph embeddings. Quan et al. (2025) demonstrate that constraining entity representations to a hypersphere creates an "inherently hard negative sampling" environment, forcing models to learn more robust and semantically coherent representations. This geometric regularization aligns perfectly with our normalized embedding assumption and provides theoretical justification for spherical constraints.

2.3 Contribution Metrics and Manipulation Resistance

The h‑index (Hirsch, 2005) captures sustained output but ignores content and temporal dynamics. PageRank (Page et al., 1999) captures network centrality but is content‑agnostic and linearly vulnerable to Sybil attacks, as established by Cheng and Friedman (2005). TrustRank (Gyöngyi et al., 2004) and EigenTrust (Kamvar et al., 2003) introduce heuristics for trust‑weighted propagation in peer‑to‑peer networks, but neither provides formal bounds on the gain achievable by a colluding coalition.

TraceRank and transaction‑value weighting. Shi and Shi (2025) introduce TraceRank, a reputation‑weighted ranking algorithm for payment graphs where payment transactions serve as endorsements . Reputation propagates through payment flows weighted by transaction value and temporal recency according to:

F_{j\to i} = \sum_{e\in \mathcal{E}_{j\to i}}\left[\log(1+\text{value}_{\text{USD}}(e)) \cdot e^{-\lambda \,\text{age}_{\text{days}}(e)}\right]

After normalization to obtain column-stochastic transition weights, TraceRank iterates:

\mathbf{r}^{(t+1)} = \mathbf{s} + \alpha W^\top \mathbf{r}^{(t)}

converging to $\mathbf{r} = (I - \alpha W^\top)^{-1}\mathbf{s}$ . Crucially, they argue that "reputation propagation resists Sybil attacks by making spam services with many low‑reputation payers rank below legitimate services with few high‑reputation payers." We incorporate this insight to strengthen our manipulation resistance bounds.

2.4 Stochastic Information Geometry and Distributed Inference

Ghatak (2025) develops a unified framework integrating stochastic geometry with information geometry for distributed inference. Key contributions include:

· Characterization of Fréchet means of Gaussian fields indexed by Poisson point processes
· Non‑asymptotic concentration bounds and Palm deviations for empirical means
· Geometry‑aware aggregation methods that downweight unreliable sensors

This framework provides the mathematical tools to extend our deterministic dynamics to stochastic settings, enabling confidence intervals and robustness guarantees.

2.5 Cold‑Start Problems in Temporal Networks

Xie et al. (2025) address influence maximization with cold‑start nodes—nodes with no history. Their approach uses motif‑based labeling and tensorized Temporal Graph Networks (TGNs) for multi‑relational temporal graphs, augmented by providing cold‑start nodes with neighbors from historical data sharing similar Influence Propagation Paths. This methodology directly applies to validating our Contribution Index for new nodes entering an epistemic network.

2.6 Spectral Measures of Epistemic Emergence

Bailey and Schneider (2025) propose $\Phi_{\text{spectral}}$, a scalable spectral approximation of integrated information that measures epistemic emergence—the degree to which a system forms an integrated whole irreducible to its components . Using the Fiedler vector of the normalized Laplacian to define a minimal bipartition, $\Phi_{\text{spectral}}$ sums mutual information to estimate informational disintegration:

\Phi_{\text{spectral}} = \sum_{k=1}^m I(X^k; X^k_{\text{other}})

This measure detects transient integration in transitional systems and reveals the collapse of complexity in fixed‑point convergent networks . This connects directly to our Epistemic Laplacian and provides a complementary measure of system‑level integration.

2.7 The Gap This Thesis Fills

No unified mathematical framework combines temporal Volterra dynamics, knowledge recombination originality , spherical geometric embeddings , transaction‑value weighted Sybil resistance , stochastic information geometry, and spectral emergence measures . This thesis bridges these domains while maintaining rigorous analytical guarantees.

